'''Benjamin Peter Waine''' (born 11 June 2001) is a New Zealand professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|PortVale}} club [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] and the [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand national team]].

Waine began his career with [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]], playing for the [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|Reserves]] in the [[New Zealand Football Championship]]. He made his [[A-League Men|A-League]] debut in August 2018, becoming the youngest player and goalscorer in the club's history at age 17 and 18, respectively. He was sold to English club [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] in December 2022, who he helped to win the [[EFL League One|League One]] title at the end of the 2022–23 season. He spent the 2024–25 campaign on loan at [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]]. He left Plymouth in June 2025 and signed for Port Vale.

He represented New Zealand at [[New Zealand men's national under-20 football team|under-20]] and [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|under-23]] level, competing at the [[2020 Summer Olympics|2020]] and [[2024 Summer Olympics]]. He made his debut for the senior team in March 2022 and won the [[2024 OFC Nations Cup]], scoring four goals in the tournament.

==Early and personal life==
Benjamin Peter Waine was born on 11 June 2001 in [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]]. He attended school at [[Hutt International Boys' School]] in [[Upper Hutt]], where he was the Junior school captain in 2019.<ref name="callup" /> He is a [[Multiple citizenship|dual citizen]] of New Zealand and the [[United Kingdom]], as his parents are both from England.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Errington |first=Chris |date=3 January 2023 |title=The story behind Ben Waine and his move to Argyle. In his spare time he enjoys driving monster trucks. |url=https://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/sport/football/story-behind-ben-waine-move-7986203 |access-date=22 April 2023 |website=PlymouthLive |language=en}}</ref> He supports [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] as his mother's family are [[Geordie]]s.<ref name="laforge">{{cite news |last1=Baggaley |first1=Mike |title=Taking the Vale opportunity |url=https://portvalethevaliant.substack.com/p/taking-the-vale-opportunity |access-date=20 July 2025 |work=Valiant's Substack |date=20 July 2025}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Wellington Phoenix===
Waine joined the Academy at [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]] at the age of 14.<ref name="laforge"/> On 7 August 2018, Waine made his debut for the senior side in their [[Australia Cup|FFA Cup]] loss to [[Bentleigh Greens SC|Bentleigh Greens]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hyslop |first1=Liam |title=Wellington Phoenix fall to 10-man NPL team Bentleigh Greens in FFA Cup |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/106090205/wellington-phoenix-fall-to-10man-npl-team-bentleigh-greens-in-ffa-cup |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=7 August 2018 |accessdate=1 April 2019}}</ref> At the age of 17 years and 57 days, this made him the [[Wellington Phoenix FC records and statistics|youngest player in the club's history]].<ref>{{cite web |title=ALeague Stats |url=https://aleaguestats.com/A-League_6WellingtonPhoenix.html |website=aleaguestats.com |access-date=1 July 2025}}</ref> He played most of his games for the [[Wellington Phoenix FC Reserves|Wellington Phoenix Reserves]] in the [[New Zealand Football Championship]], scoring a team high of eight goals, before head coach [[Marko Rudan]] called up to the senior team again in March.<ref name="callup">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Phoenix coach promotes Wellington schoolboy Ben Waine |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/111331473/phoenix-coach-promotes-wellington-teenager-ben-waine |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=16 March 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref> On 30 March, Waine made his league debut for the Phoenix, coming on as a [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] in their 4–1 win over the [[Newcastle Jets FC|Newcastle Jets]] at the [[Wellington Regional Stadium|Westpac Stadium]].<ref name="debut">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Possible season-ending injury to Louis Fenton sours Wellington Phoenix win |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/111676078/possible-seasonending-injury-to-louis-fenton-sours-wellington-phoenix-win |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref> On 28 April, he made his first league start for the Phoenix in a 5–0 loss to the [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]].<ref name="start">{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix suffer biggest defeat under coach Mark Rudan |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/112282729/wellington-phoenix-suffer-biggest-defeat-under-coach-mark-rudan |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=28 April 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref>

In June 2019, Waine signed a two-year contract with the Phoenix. The first year was a scholarship deal, with the second year moving him onto a full-time contract.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix lock in hometown product Ben Waine on two-year deal |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/113656283/wellington-phoenix-lock-in-hometown-product-ben-waine-on-twoyear-deal |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=21 June 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref> Just before the [[2019–20 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2019–20]] season kicked off, the first year of this contract was upgraded to full-time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Ben Waine earns contract upgrade as Wellington Phoenix hit the magic 20 mark |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/116511620/ben-waine-earns-contract-upgrade-as-wellington-phoenix-hit-the-magic-20-mark |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=11 October 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref> On 3 November, Waine scored his first professional goal off the bench in Wellington's 3–2 loss to [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] to become the youngest goalscorer in the club's history at 18 years and 145 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Wellington Phoenix fume over handball howler in Melbourne City defeat |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/117132923/wellington-phoenix-fume-over-handball-howler-in-controversial-melbourne-city-defeat |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=3 November 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref> He continued to score goals for [[Chris Greenacre]]'s Reserve team, before injuries to [[Tomer Hemed]] and [[Jaushua Sotirio]] and a suspension for [[David Ball (footballer)|David Ball]] gave him the opportunity to play games for the senior team.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=Wellington Phoenix young gun Ben Waine found the perfect mentor at the perfect time |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/124976826/wellington-phoenix-young-gun-ben-waine-found-the-perfect-mentor-at-the-perfect-time |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=30 April 2021}}</ref> He established himself as a key player in the [[2020–21 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2020–21]] campaign, becoming the youngest Phoenix player to score five A-League goals in a single season, and the fourth player in the club's history to score in four consecutive games, securing himself a nomination for A-League Young Footballer of the Year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Waine Commits To Wellington Phoenix For Three Years |url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/ben-waine-commits-wellington-phoenix-three-years/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Wellington Phoenix |date=20 May 2021 |language=en-AU}}</ref><ref name="woody">{{cite news |title=Stags recruit new forward |url=https://www.mansfieldtown.net/news/2024/august/30/stags-recruit-new-forward/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Mansfield Town FC |date=30 August 2024}}</ref> He rejected an offer from English club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] to instead sign a new three-year deal with Wellington.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=England move to stay with Wellington Phoenix |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/a-league/125192111/teen-star-ben-waine-turns-down-england-move-to-stay-with-wellington-phoenix |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=20 May 2021}}</ref>

Waine scored six league goals in the [[2021–22 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2021–22]] season, finishing as the club's joint top-scorer alongside [[Gael Sandoval]] and [[Jaushua Sotirio]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jensen |first1=Nick |title=Wellington Phoenix 2022/23 Season Preview |url=https://thefootballsack.com.au/2022/10/wellington-phoenix-2022-23-season-preview.html |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=The Football Sack |date=5 October 2022}}</ref> He began the [[2022–23 Wellington Phoenix FC season|2022–23]] campaign in good scoring form, hitting three goals as Wellington reached the quarter-finals of the FFA Cup.<ref>{{cite news |title=Getting Amongst The Tale Of Ben Waine's Transfer To Plymouth Argyle |url=https://theniche-cache.com/football/2023/1/4/getting-amongst-the-tale-of-ben-waines-transfer-to-plymouth-argyle |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=The Niche Cache |date=4 January 2023}}</ref> He scored a total of 17 goals in 73 [[A-League Men|A-League]] matches, and was dubbed the "Waine Train" by Nix fans before he departed at the age of 21, with head coach [[Ufuk Talay]] remarking that "''he's hopefully going off to bigger and better things and continues to have success in his career''".<ref>{{cite news |title='Waine Train' departs Wellington |url=https://wellingtonphoenix.com/news/waine-train-departs-wellington/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Wellington Phoenix |date=30 December 2022 |language=en-AU}}</ref>

===Plymouth Argyle===
On 30 December 2022, Waine agreed to join English [[EFL League One|League One]] leaders [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth Argyle]] for an undisclosed six-figure fee on a two-and-a-half-year deal, the transfer going through on 1 January when the transfer window opened.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Waine Signs {{!}} Plymouth Argyle - PAFC |url=https://www.pafc.co.uk/news/ben-waine-signs |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Plymouth Argyle FC |date=30 December 2022 |language=en}}</ref> Director of football [[Neil Dewsnip]] confirmed that the club had first attempted to sign the player the previous summer.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Waine reveals the advice behind his long-distance deal with Plymouth Argyle |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2022/12/31/ben-waine-reveals-the-advice-behind-his-long-distance-deal-with-plymouth-argyle/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Friends of Football |date=30 December 2022 |language=en-NZ}}</ref> He made his first start for the Pilgrims on 4 February, leading the line in a 3–4–2–1 formation in a 1–0 defeat at [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], though was taken off at half-time for tactical reasons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Errington |first1=Chris |title=Schumacher explains Waine start for Argyle at Sheffield Wednesday |url=https://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/sport/football/steven-schumacher-explains-ben-waine-8113756 |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Plymouth Live |date=6 February 2023 |language=en}}</ref> He scored two goals in 11 matches in the second half of the [[2022–23 Plymouth Argyle F.C. season|2022–23]] promotion-winning season, though was behind [[Ryan Hardie]] and [[Niall Ennis]] in the pecking order and missed the later stages after picking up an ankle injury.<ref name="pace"/><ref>{{cite news |title=All Whites striker Ben Waine tipped for big things ahead of new English season |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2023/08/05/all-whites-striker-ben-waine-tipped-for-big-things-ahead-of-new-english-season/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Friends of Football |date=4 August 2023 |language=en-NZ}}</ref>

Now in the [[EFL Championship|Championship]], he made nine starts and 23 substitute appearances in the league in the [[2023–24 Plymouth Argyle F.C. season|2023–24]] season, scoring two goals.<ref name="pace"/> He also scored three goals in the [[EFL Cup]], including against [[Premier League]] club [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] at [[Home Park]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Errington |first1=Chris |title=Steven Schumacher outlines Ben Waine progress at Argyle |url=https://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/sport/football/steven-schumacher-outlines-ben-waine-8716572 |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Plymouth Live |date=31 August 2023 |language=en}}</ref> Speaking in November, manager [[Steven Schumacher]] said that "''he's desperate to learn, he's desperate to get better and I think we're seeing that in his performances''".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Waine: Plymouth Argyle striker 'desperate to learn' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67514373 |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=BBC Sport |date=23 November 2023}}</ref> Schumacher left the club in January and new manager [[Ian Foster (footballer)|Ian Foster]] continued to give him opportunities off the bench ahead of [[Mustapha Bundu]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rooke |first1=Jamie |title=Ian Foster's Plymouth decisions may concern Mustapha Bundu |url=https://footballleagueworld.co.uk/new-argyle-boss-ian-foster-substitute-decision-is-cause-for-concern-for-greens-striker-view/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=FootballLeagueWorld |date=16 January 2024 |language=en}}</ref>

He featured on the left of an attacking trio in two of the new manager [[Wayne Rooney]]'s opening three games of the [[2024–25 Plymouth Argyle F.C. season|2024–25]] campaign.<ref name="pace"/><ref>{{cite news |title=All Whites striker Ben Waine keen to learn from new boss Wayne Rooney |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2024/08/19/all-whites-striker-ben-waine-keen-to-learn-from-new-boss-wayne-rooney/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Friends of Football |date=18 August 2024 |language=en-NZ}}</ref> On 30 August 2024, Waine returned to League One with [[Mansfield Town F.C.|Mansfield Town]] on a season-long [[Loan (sport)|loan]] to gain some more game time at [[Field Mill]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=30 August 2024 |title=Ben Waine: Mansfield Town sign Plymouth Argyle forward on loan |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c1w75rpv90do |access-date=16 September 2024 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> He started two league games for the Stags, scoring three goals in 29 overall appearances.<ref name=sb2425/> Manager [[Nigel Clough]] explained that "''if we were halfway up the league or something like that, or in a better run, he would have played more, but his attitude has been absolutely fantastic all season''".<ref>{{cite news |title=All Whites forward Ben Waine joins English League One club Port Vale |url=https://www.friendsoffootballnz.com/2025/07/01/all-whites-forward-ben-waine-joins-english-league-one-club-port-vale/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Friends of Football |date=30 June 2025 |language=en-NZ}}</ref> He left Plymouth Argyle after the relegated club opted against taking up a 12-month extension on his contract.<ref name="pace">{{cite news |last1=Errington |first1=Chris |title=Argyle took swing and a miss with Ben Waine signing |url=https://www.plymouthherald.co.uk/sport/football/plymouth-argyle-swing-miss-waine-10165360 |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Plymouth Live |date=9 May 2025 |language=en}}</ref>

===Port Vale===
On 30 June 2025, Waine agreed to join newly-promoted League One club [[Port Vale F.C.|Port Vale]] on a two-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Waine: Port Vale sign New Zealand striker on free transfer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cx2nnxggrdvo |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=BBC Sport |date=1 July 2025}}</ref> Manager [[Darren Moore]] said that "''he's a young striker who will come in and give us something different''".<ref>{{cite news |title=Ben Waine is a Valiant! |url=https://www.port-vale.co.uk/news/ben-waine-valiant |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=Port Vale FC |date=30 June 2025 |language=en}}</ref> However, Waine fell down the pecking order following the deadline day signing of [[Devante Cole]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harby |first1=Chris |last2=Bowers |first2=Phil |title=Ben Waine: Port Vale forward stays positive after being dropped |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c36zkewr02no |access-date=8 December 2025 |work=BBC Sport |date=8 December 2025}}</ref> He scored his first two goals for the club playing on the left wing at the start of December, having not played a game for the club since September.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baggaley |first1=Mike |title=Vale's FA Cup boost |url=https://portvalethevaliant.substack.com/p/vales-fa-cup-boost |access-date=7 December 2025 |work=Valiant's Substack |date=7 December 2025}}</ref> New manager [[Jon Brady]] played him as part of a front two.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baggaley |first1=Mike |title=Hernandez and Ward sign up |url=https://portvalethevaliant.substack.com/p/hernandez-and-ward-sign-up |access-date=10 February 2026 |work=Valiant's Substack |date=9 February 2026}}</ref> On 3 March 2026, he scored an extra-time winner against [[Bristol City F.C.|Bristol City]] to put the Vale into the fifth round of the [[FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=De Cosemo |first1=Harry |title=FA Cup: Port Vale 1-0 Bristol City: Waine strike sends Vale into fifth-round |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c70nwk6pj34t |access-date=4 March 2026 |work=BBC Sport |date=3 March 2026}}</ref> Five days later, he scored the only goal of the game against [[Premier League]] side [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in the fifth round, and celebrated the goal in the style of [[Alan Shearer]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lansley |first1=Peter |title=Port Vale stun Sunderland to reach first FA Cup quarter-final in 72 years |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2026/mar/08/port-vale-sunderland-fa-cup-match-report |access-date=9 March 2026 |work=The Guardian |date=8 March 2026}}</ref> This later won him the club's Goal of the Season award.<ref name="POTY">{{cite news |title=Kyle John named Port Vale Player of the Season |url=https://www.port-vale.co.uk/news/kyle-john-named-port-vale-player-season |access-date=27 April 2026 |work=Port Vale FC |date=27 April 2026 |language=en}}</ref> His eight goals made him the club's joint top scorer in the [[2025–26 Port Vale F.C. season|2025–26]] season, which culminated in relegation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baggaley |first1=Mike |title=A season rated |url=https://portvalethevaliant.substack.com/p/a-season-rated |access-date=4 May 2026 |work=Valiant's Substack |date=4 May 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
On 16 April 2019, Waine was selected as one of the 21 players for the [[New Zealand men's national under-20 football team|New Zealand U-20]] who played at the [[2019 FIFA U-20 World Cup]] in Poland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Top talent named in U-20 squad |url=https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/75691 |website=[[New Zealand Football]] |accessdate=16 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416121832/https://www.nzfootball.co.nz/newsarticle/75691 |archive-date=16 April 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref> He scored a brace in their opening match against [[Honduras national under-20 football team|Honduras]] on 24 May. He made two further appearances in the tournament, starting in both New Zealand's 2–0 victory over [[Norway national under-20 football team|Norway]] and the 1–1 loss on penalties to [[Colombia national under-20 football team|Colombia]] in the Round of 16. In September, Waine was a member of the [[New Zealand men's national under-23 football team|New Zealand U-23]] team, known as the "Oly-Whites", who took part in the [[2019 OFC Men's Olympic Qualifying Tournament|2019 OFC Olympic Qualifying Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ben Waine focussed on fulfilling Olympic dream |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/ben-waine-focussed-on-fulfilling-olympic-dream/ |website=[[Oceania Football Confederation]] |date=3 October 2019 |accessdate=3 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=OlyWhites make late change as Callum McCowatt stays with Wellington Phoenix |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/115847658/olywhites-make-late-change-as-callum-mccowatt-stays-with-wellington-phoenix |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=18 September 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref> He was second top goal scorer for the tournament with eight goals including one in the final, helping New Zealand to qualify for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Zealand U-23 secure Olympic qualification |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/new-zealand-u-23-secure-olympic-qualification/ |website=[[Oceania Football Confederation]] |date=5 October 2019 |accessdate=5 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191006060940/https://www.oceaniafootball.com/new-zealand-u-23-secure-olympic-qualification/ |archive-date=6 October 2019 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Voerman |first1=Andrew |title=OlyWhites ease past Solomon Islands to book their place at the Tokyo Olympics |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/116349208/olywhites-ease-past-solomon-islands-to-book-their-place-at-the-tokyo-olympics |publisher=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=5 October 2019 |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref> He went on to compete at the [[2024 Summer Olympics]] in Paris, scoring the winning goal against [[Guinea national under-23 football team|Guinea]] at the [[Allianz Riviera]] in the [[Football at the 2024 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament – Group A|group stages]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Guinea 1–2 New Zealand |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/match-centre/match/512/286056/286057/400018527 |website=FIFA |access-date=1 July 2025}}</ref>

Waine made his [[New Zealand men's national football team|senior]] international debut on 18 March 2022, scoring his first senior international goal in New Zealand's [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (OFC)|World Cup qualification]] match against [[Papua New Guinea national soccer team|Papua New Guinea]], winning the game 1–0.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rollo |first1=Phillip |title=Ben Waine saves All Whites' blushes with late goal against Papua New Guinea |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/sport/football/nz-teams/128100316/ben-waine-saves-all-whites-blushes-with-late-goal-against-papua-new-guinea |work=[[Stuff (website)|Stuff]] |date=18 March 2022 |language=en |accessdate=1 July 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Burgess |first1=Michael |title=Untidy All Whites claim first win of World Cup qualifying tournament |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/football/football-world-cup/football-untidy-all-whites-edge-papua-new-guinea-in-opening-match-of-ofc-world-cup-qualifying-tournament/I47DYBK5HGVQBTOYT66SNDETTM/ |access-date=1 July 2025 |work=NZ Herald |date=18 March 2022 |language=en-NZ}}</ref> He established himself as the back up to captain [[Chris Wood (footballer, born 1991)|Chris Wood]].<ref name="woody"/> He scored four goals at the [[2024 OFC Nations Cup]] and played the first 73 minutes of [[2024 OFC Men's Nations Cup final|the final]], a 3–0 victory over [[Vanuatu national football team|Vanuatu]].<ref name=Vanuatu>{{cite web |title=Match |url=https://www.oceaniafootball.com/competition-list/ofc-mens-nations-cup-2024-final-2700242851/winner-semi-final-1-winner-semi-final-2-2701560131/ |website=Oceania Football Confederation |access-date=1 July 2025}}</ref> He was named in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup squads|squad]] for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]] in North America by head coach [[Darren Bazeley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New Zealand name World Cup squad |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/tournaments/mens/worldcup/canadamexicousa2026/articles/new-zealand-squad-named |access-date=14 May 2026 |work=FIFA |date=13 May 2026}}</ref>

==Style of play==
